Name: CRI Headless Halloween Regatta
Description: CRI's Third Annual Halloween Headless Regatta, Sunday October 31st.Racing begins at 9:00.Sign up to race in the highlight event of the CRI scullers' calendar, the Halloween Headless Regatta! We've got several race categories, lots of ways to win prizes, (including awards for Best Costume, Best Rowing Style, Best Costume on the Dock) and the best post-race brunch this side of the Mississippi. The race follows a moderately buoyed course from near the HOCR finish line upstream to conclude right in front of our Harry Parker Boathouse. Even if you've never raced before, this is one event you must try. When else can you be cheered across the line by people in wild make-up and outrageous costumes? And what other regatta signals that you've crossed by blowing a clown horn?The race is open to a wide range of boats (B boats and tubbies included). To sign up, email Chris Flynn at cflynnusa@netscape.net.And if you're interested in volunteering, email me at henriettepower@mac.com.  And, finally, be on the lookout for information about how to order a fabulous regatta t-shirt, designed by sculler/artist extraordinaire, Molly Scannell.-The Sculling Captains

Name: CRI Headless Halloween Regatta
Description: Right! Here is everything you need to know about tomorrow's Second Annual Halloween Headless Regatta!8:00 Volunteers (except set-up people) show up at boathouse8:30 Set-up volunteers show up8:30 Meeting for all racers (racers should be ready to launch immediately after the very brief meeting)8:35 boats launch!9:00 racing begins (schedule of all races, including bow numbers, will be posted to the group in just a few minutes)Racing will finish soon after 10:00, at which point we'll all gather for pot-luck brunch, merriment, and AWARDS!Additional information:Handicapping: if you would like to have your time handicapped, and if you are over thirty, email Chris Flynn (p.cflynn@mac.com) with your  age sometime today. Those racing in the Women's 2x and the Mixed 2x please note that three of the boats in the Women's race are being used again in the Mixed race (see schedule). Don't go hide them somewhere when you're done racing!If you have any questions, feel free to email either me (henriettepower@mac.com) or Chris.See you ALL tomorrow!

Name: Crash B's Indoor Rowing World Championship
Description: The 2011 C.R.A.S.H.-B. Sprints will be held on Sunday, February 20, 2010 at Boston University’s Agganis Arena. Doors open at 7:00am. The C.R.A.S.H.-B. Sprints is a one-day event with racing scheduled from 9:00 AM – 5:00 PM. Admission is free to all spectators.C.R.A.S.H.-B. Sprints offers Adaptive, Able-bodied, and Coxswain (non-Rower) events for 2011.  Adaptive athletes will race 1000m in the Paralympic rowing categories for Open Men and Women (no age restriction) as well as in an FES category. Paralympic events are also offered to Junior Men and Women.  Able-bodied athletes will race 2000m.  The Coxswain event (a non-rower’s event which is open traditionally to coxswains only, not flyweight rowers) is also 2000m. Competitors row against the clock on Concept2 Model D Ergometers.Hammers are awarded to overall winners in all events, medals for 2nd and 3rd places, as well aspecial recognition medals for the top US collegiate finisher in each of the Open and Lightweight categories for the Men’s and Women’s events.Please continue to check the C.R.A.S.H.-B. web site for updated information regarding the 2011 Regatta including online Registration, schedules, events, hotels, etc.  Follow us on twitterand facebook so you can receive up to the minute notification of new information.

Name: Heineken Roeivierkamp
Description: The Heineken Roeivierkamp, organised by the Amsterdam rowing club Nereus, is a multiple distance 2-day rowing regatta. It is the traditional opening of the Dutch rowing season and it is known for its unique format. Over the past 38 years this race has received a lot of international attention and it attracts more and more crews who want to benefit from the oppor- tunity to compete against Dutch and international crews, from club level to international SA level.The format of the race is copied from the speed skating all-round champi- onships, though the distances are divided by two: 250m, 750m, 2500m and 5000m. The scores on the separate distances are converted to 250m times; the sum of these converted times provide the final score. This format makes the regatta more challenging than other races; crews need to have the stamina to perform at long-distance but also need the skills for a short sprint.To make the races even more competitive, the bow order for the distances on Sunday (750m and 5000m) is determined by the crew’s place in the intermediate ranking; the highest ranked crews start last. This guarantees spectacular races and calls the need for skilful coxing.On saturday the crews take of for the 2500m and 250m. The 2500 is rowed ‘Head’ style; crews start with 20 second intervals. Your cox will be able to practice his or her coxing skills for the first time when you pass the ‘Omval’ (see course map on next page). Directly after this warming-up your cox has to steer right in the explosive head-to-head 250m - remember one second loss on the 250 is 20 seconds to make up for on the 5000m! On sunday morning the Masters and Club crews are allowed to sleep a bit longer, but the others get up for the killer 750, the most underestimated distance. It’s not a sprint, but neither a 2K. Sunday afternoon the H4K is concluded with the 5000m. As said, the startingorder is the reversed classificition, so you are com- peting against your direct opponent. Coxing makes the dif- ference here; you can easily win or loose 10 seconds in the ‘Grote Bocht’ (‘Big Bend’). Sunday evening, after the prize giving ceremony, a grand party with top-class DJ’s takes off at Nereus. At 12:00 p.m. we have a short break to let the Dutch rowers out - but the party continues for our foreign guests and spectators.The Heineken Roeivierkamp is known for its unique atmos- phere. More than 2500 participants transform the river Amstel into a huge arena in which only the strongest survive. The audience of more than 10.000 people will not only be entertained by this visual spectacle but is also served by our ‘Racing Reporters’ who comment the Heineken regatta the whole weekend via FM radio, in “Dutch touch”.

Name: NSR #1
Description: USRowing selects, trains and manages the teams that represent the U.S. in international competition including the world championships, Pan American Games and Olympics.USRowing’s senior national team represents the U.S. at the highest level of international competition, either at the Olympic Games or the World Championships. These athletes also compete at the Rowing World Cups and the Pan American Games.

Name: San Diego Crew Classic
Description: On April 2 & 3, 2011 collegiate, junior and masters athletes will return to the sun-kissed water of Mission Bay for the 38th renewal of the Crew Classic and compete in 90 races over two days. Across seven lanes, with the city skyline as a backdrop, they will race for early season honors and coveted trophies.  Again they will be cheered by spectators enjoying amenities such as the shore-side tent row for alumni and clubs, the jumbotron displaying races start to finish, a beer garden on the sand, and much more...

Name: CRI Rumble on the River
Description: The 2nd Annual Rumble on the River will draw crowds to the banks of the Charles for extraordinary racing between military veterans, adaptive rowers, junior competitive teams, and collegiate rivals. The festival scene will occur at CRI’s award winning Harry Parker Boathouse and will feature exciting races, six up and coming bands, a jumbo-tron for live commentary, games, and barbeque. A full afternoon of events will include US Paralympian Rowers, US Military Veterans, CRI Youth rowers, and G-Row girls and Boys Row boys from Boston. Between the races there will be music from up and coming Boston bands Pimps of Joytime, Roots of Creation, Sea Monsters, Ghosts of Jupiter, Dub Apocalypse, and Banana Phonetic.The 2nd year of the event, is a unique opportunity to introduce non-rowers to the sport of rowing, with a chance to see racing at all levels, from beginners to elites. The event will feature head to head racing along the banks of the Charles River. Races will be announced, so attendees will be able to follow the action and learn more about the sport.

Name: CRI Headless Halloween Regatta
Description: November?.......but Halloween is in October!!  True, but the Head of the Fish Regatta in Saratoga Springs, NY has taken our traditional Halloween weekend date and many of CRI’s singles and doubles will be up there and not available to us.  So continue in the Halloween spirit for a little longer and come race with us. In costume of course!! The race follows a moderately buoyed course that starts near the HOCR finish line and ends right in front of the CRI docks.  We meet at 8:30am , launch at 8:35am, and  racing begins at 9:00am.  This race is open to everyone – adaptive, tubbies, B boats, singles and doubles, even if you’ve never raced before!!  The entrance fee is easy also – a costume and something to share at our post-race brunch.  There will be several race categories and lots of ways to win prizes (Best Costume, Best Rowing Style as well as 1st, 2nd, and 3rd in each category).To sign up, email Liz Kosturko at lizkosturko@gmail.com or Lynn Salmonsen at lyns@mindspring.com.  Include your name, age and 1st and 2nd boat choices or a private boat.And if you’d like to volunteer email me at Lyns@mindspring.com .  We’ll  need launch drivers, dock hands, photographers, and people to set up and take down brunch.

Name: Women's Eastern Sprints 2012
Description: Women's Eastern Sprints refers to the annual rowing championship for the Eastern Association of Women's Rowing Colleges (EAWRC) league. The teams include all of the Ivy League schools as well as others such as MIT, BU, and Wisconsin. The race is held on the Cooper River in Camden, New Jersey.

Name: Big East Women's Championship
Description: The Caspersen Rowing Center, operated by the Princeton National Rowing Association, will serve as the headquarters for the BIG EAST Championship, which will be conducted for the ninth time in 2012. The facility has hosted some of the highest-level regattas in the sport, including four Olympic Team Trials, the 2002-09 USRowing National Selection Regattas and the 2006 NCAA Championship."Our philosophy in awarding championship sites is to always provide for a positive and memorable experience for our student-athletes," said BIG EAST Associate Commissioner for Olympic Sports James Siedliski. "With that in mind, we're thrilled to be able to conduct our rowing championship at a world-class facility that will allow our student-athletes the chance to perform at their highest levels.""The Princeton National Rowing Association is excited that the BIG EAST Conference has chosen Mercer Lake and the Caspersen Rowing Center as the site for this year's BIG EAST Championship," said Princeton National Rowing Association Director Kristopher Grudt. "Mercer Lake is one of the finest rowing venues in the country and it is great to be able to bring this high caliber of competition to Mercer County. With the 2012 NCAA Women's Rowing Championship and the 2012 Olympic Team Trials scheduled for Mercer Lake, it will be a great opportunity for the athletes to get race experience on this course.""We are tremendously excited to host the BIG EAST Rowing Championship at Mercer Lake for the first time," said Mercer County executive Brian M. Hughes. "Mercer Lake is home to an Olympic training site that prepares our nation's top rowers for competition on the world stage and we are eager to showcase the best of BIG EAST rowing in May."
Subtitle: Mercer Lake, NJ

Name: Tufts University Races #4
Description: Simmons College, Smith College, Wellesley College, and Tufts University Women's Crews will compete onthe Malden River Saturday, April 28, 2012 in the 5th Annual Malden River Spirit Regatta. The TuftsUniversity Varsity Women’s Eight won the inaugural event in a nail biting finish in 2008. Smith Collegesurged out to an early lead and rowed to a comfortable seven second victory in the 2009 grand final, over adetermined Tufts crew, Simmons College rowed away to a determined 5.5 second win over Smith in the2010 championship race, and Wellesley College made it four winners in four years with a decisive win in the2011 Grand Finals. The Malden River Spirit Award is emblematic of supremacy in the race series which hasbeen held annually on the Malden River since 2002. The award represents the tradition of competitive spiritand sportsmanship exemplified by the coaches and athletes of the three guest schools as well as the athletesfrom Tufts, and has been commissioned and donated by the Tufts Coaching Staff.Saturday is also Senior Day at Shoemaker Boathouse and the final home race for the class of 2012. Seniorwomen’s crew co-captains, Maggie Debski, Kathleen Holec, and Erika Parisi will be making their finalracing sojourns on the Malden River Saturday morning along with classmates Kara Breen, Lily Carey,Georgia Gunner, Miriam Gutman, and Gillian Hodes. Men’s co-captain Chris Park and teammate MichaelBai will also be honored. Racing begins at 9:20 AM.At the conclusion of today’s racing stay and enjoy the cup presentation, view our annual Jumbo AlumniRow, and help us all say thank you to our seniors (and their families) for four terrific years as TuftsJUMBOS!The Park at River’s Edge:The Park at River's Edge is a world-class, 10-acre riverfront park with over 1/3 mile of frontage along theMalden River. The Park provides a great environment for tenants of the offices, residents of the luxuryhousing, Tufts University rowers and competitors, and anyone who enjoys a varied riverfront parkenvironment.The Park, designed by JP Shadley Associates, includes a picturesque mixture of open parkland with trees,shrubs and flowers. In constructing the Park over 8,000 plants were added including approximately 2,000plants in the 1.5 acres of wetlands which have been created or restored. The Park is irrigated with well water.The lighted Park features 100 yards of sculptured granite seat walls at multiple overlooks from which to viewthe river and other Park vistas. There are also great views from many of the 44 MWH Helmstadt Benchesstrategically located throughout the Park. For further information on the River’s Edge Park please refer tothe following web site: http://www.riversedgema.com/park.html .The William A. Shoemaker Boathouse:A highlight of the Park is the William A. Shoemaker Boathouse which houses the university’s men's andwomen's crew teams. The boathouse, which opened in 2006, was designed by Peterson Architects ofCambridge, MA. By the conclusion of racing today, Tufts will have hosted over 75 races during five regattasat River's Edge in March and April 2012, with these participating schools: Bates, Hamilton, Middlebury,Mount Holyoke, New Hampshire, Simmons, Smith, Tulane, Wellesley, Wentworth, and Wesleyan.Tufts University Crew: Visit us on the web at http://www.gotuftsjumbos.com/landing/index
Subtitle: Tufts hosting Simmons, Smith, and Wellesley
